  1. Posted at 15:51 13 Nov 202015:51 13 Nov 2020

    Vouchers suggested as alternative to office Christmas party

    Businesses are being asked to consider an alternative to the traditional Christmas office party due to coronavirus restrictions.

    The Jersey Hospitality Association (JHA) is asking businesses to give their staff vouchers to support the hospitality sector.

    This has been put in place due to the restrictions on numbers and types of entertainment allowed at venues due to the pandemic.

    It is hoped this would be a way to support the hospitality and tourism businesses which have had a difficult year.

    The offers include meals, nights in hotels and outdoor adventure experiences.

    Simon Soar, chief executive of the JHA, said: "This has been a devastating year for trading in our sector, and while we have received financial support from the government, we only had a fraction of the visitors we would normally rely on."

    Warning after fraudsters attempt to steal Â£130,000

    A business targetted in a scam that saw fraudsters intercept more than Â£130,000 has urged other companies to be extra vigilant.

    Fraudsters hacked email correspondence between a local building company and a customer and diverted payments to a scam bank account.

    They intercepted more than Â£130,000 in invoice payments.

    Taking quick action, the building company were fortunate to recover all their money but are eager to ensure other islanders don't fall victim to the same fate.

    They have raised awareness through the Jersey Fraud Prevention Forum.

    Chairman, Chief Inspector Chris Beechey says they are seeing "more and more of these impersonation scams" and other islanders might not be as lucky.

    "We're appealing to everyone to stay alert and report any new frauds and scams, no matter how small."

  3. Posted at 10:10 13 Nov 202010:10 13 Nov 2020

    Aircraft landing without clearance a 'serious incident'

    An event when a passenger aircraft came into Jersey Airport without receiving landing clearance has been described as a serious incident.

    On 5 August, the plane with two crew members and four passengers landed in Jersey Airport without the appropriate clearance.

    During the approach, Air Traffic Control (ATC) told the crew they were number one in sequence to land and instructed then to contact the Tower frequency.

    The crew then continued to approach and landed without contacting the tower or receiving clearance.

    The report reveals the crew believed they must have misinterpreted the instructions from ATC and the commander said the crew were not fatigued, distracted or overloaded.

    No one was injured or any damage caused during the incident.

    Hautlieu School staff member positive for Covid-19

    A member of staff at Hautlieu School in Jersey has tested positive for Covid-19.

    A year group and some members of staff have been asked to remain at home on Friday "as a precautionary measure" to allow testing to be completed, the Government of Jersey said.

    The secondary school has informed parents and affected areas have been deep cleaned, meaning the school will remain open.

  6. Posted at 15:44 12 Nov 202015:44 12 Nov 2020

    Jersey plans for students coming home for Christmas

    The States has announced an update on its plans to help students return home to Jersey for Christmas.

    There are about 1,700 Jersey students at overseas universities and from an initial States survey, at least 700 of those students who responded to the survey, intend to travel home for the festive period.

    The latest set of recommendations has been approved by the Competent Authorities Ministers to help overseas students travel back to Jersey.

    They have agreed upon a revised policy on testing including a slight reduction of the self-isolation period, to put a contingency plan in place for extra flights and the provision of self-isolation accommodation.

    It is hoped these provisions will support the students' "mental and physical health" and provide reassurance for their families, explained the Assistant Education Minister, Deputy Jeremy MaÃ§on.

    These plans take into account new guidance by the British government for students to travel from English universities once the lockdown ends in England.

    It describes a student travel window, which will be in place from 3-9 December.

  7. Posted at 13:12 12 Nov 202013:12 12 Nov 2020

    Contamination levels above drinking water limit near airport

    BBC Radio Jersey

    A report on water contamination has shown the levels in two boreholes near Jersey's airport are above the drinking water limit.

    The water is contaminated with the chemical PFOS.

    Boreholes in St Ouen's Bay were polluted with the same chemical in the early 90s, which was previously found in firefighting foam used at the island's airport.

    Officers say the area affected is served by a mains public water supply.

    Stuart Petrie, a consultant with Jersey's environmental health says experts are continuing to study the source of PFOS.

  8. Posted at 11:47 12 Nov 202011:47 12 Nov 2020

    Campaigners question one-site debate for new hospital

    BBC Radio Jersey

    A Jersey campaign group has questioned why politicians are only being presented with one option for the site of the island's new hospital.

    The States is due to debate whether to approve Overdale as the site for the project.

    However, the Friends of the New Hospital says it is undemocratic to give members just one option to discuss.

    The group is calling for two other States-owned sites to be included - Warwick Farm and St Saviour's Hospital.

    The island's chief minister has warned that if the Overdale site is not approved it would cost the island more money to keep the existing hospital running and delay new projects.

    But the chairman of the campaign group believes adding the other two sites into the debate will not delay the process by much.

  10. Posted at 16:36 11 Nov 202016:36 11 Nov 2020

    Hopes for 'lessons learned' after no-confidence vote

    BBC Radio Jersey

    The politician who initiated the vote of no confidence in Jersey Chief Minister John Le Fondre said she hopes ministers will learn lessons from the issues raised in the States debate.

    Senator Kristina Moore's proposal was defeated, with 29 politicians voting to keep Senator Le Fondre in his role.

    She said the public response on both sides of the argument showed why it was "an important debate to have" and for States members to have their say.

    She added: "Hopefully we'll see change and hopefully some members of the government will have listened and have learned some lessons."

    Mr Le Fondre said it was important to draw a line under what had happened and move on.

    He said: "As long as we have rational debates, hopefully all members can address each issue as it comes along and on the merits of that issue."

  11. Posted at 14:57 11 Nov 202014:57 11 Nov 2020

    Family proud of Jersey veteran who attended Unknown Warrior ceremony

    BBC Radio Jersey

    Mary BartlettCopyright: Mary Bartlett

    The daughter of a decorated World War One veteran from Jersey has shared pictures of her father attending the ceremony where the Unknown Warrior was laid to rest, 100 years ago.

    Francis Noble was part of the Royal Navy contingent of the Guard of Valour attending the ceremony at Westminster Abbey on 11 November, 1920.

    He received the British Conspicuous Gallantry Medal for his actions fighting the Ottoman Empire in Yemen in 1917, where he left cover and brought in a marine who was fatally wounded from an exposed position.

    Mary BartlettCopyright: Mary Bartlett

    Mary Bartlett said her father, who also received the French Medaille Militaire, would not share stories from the war and much of what she knows about his action has emerged after her son found his gallantry citation.

    She said she does not know what her father did to be honoured by the French.

    Mrs Bartlett added her father's presence at the ceremony for the Unknown Warrior gave her a "very great sense of pride".

    She was only a baby when her father attended the ceremony, but she emphasised the tomb's importance in ensuring those lost in war would "never be forgotten".

    "That was the first world war, but we've had a second since and I remember it.

    "I was here in the Occupation, so I remember Liberation Day as well."

    Income Support claims see slight drop - economic report

    Andrew Segal

    BBC News

    Income Support claims in Jersey have seen a slight drop in just over a week, according to Statistics Jersey's latest economic indicators report.

    The full report said that, on 1 November, there were 6,090 active claims - 20 lower compared with 25 October 2020, but 510 more than a year earlier on 31 October 2019.

    The report added that, under Phase Two of the Government Co-Funded Payroll Scheme, almost Â£78.6m had been paid out for a total 13,610 claims for April, May, June, July and August 2020.

    Phase Three of the payroll scheme had seen almost Â£5.2m had been paid out for a total 1,180 claims for September 2020.

    The report said that public transport usage was 44% lower than a year earlier.

  13. Posted at 10:29 11 Nov 202010:29 11 Nov 2020

    Health bosses unsure how much vaccine Jersey will get

    BBC Radio Jersey

    Jersey's health authorities have said they are unsure how many doses of coronavirus vaccine the island will get once its approved for use.

    Pharmaceutical company Pfizer has said it has developed one that could prevent 90% of people from getting the illness, although it is not yet clear how long immunity lasts, or whether it works in older people.

    Jersey officials have struck a deal with the UK's NHS to import the vaccine via usual supply lines once it is approved for use, and are looking at potential sites for vaccine centres.

    Becky Sherrington, from the vaccine delivery team, said many older islanders could be given it as a priority.

    Quote Message: The demand will probably be higher than the amount that we have, so we really need to make sure that people understand that we'll be doing it as fast as we possibly can."

    The demand will probably be higher than the amount that we have, so we really need to make sure that people understand that we'll be doing it as fast as we possibly can."

    Figures show there are currently 126 people known to have Covid-19 in Jersey.

  14. Posted at 10:17 11 Nov 202010:17 11 Nov 2020

    Returning students could be offered self-isolation hostels

    BBC Radio Jersey

    Jersey students returning to the island for Christmas could be offered the option of isolation in dedicated hostels if they cannot quarantine at home.

    Government ministers are meeting on Wednesday to agree appropriate policies for young people coming back from university.

    It comes as new guidance has been issued to universities in England, explaining how students can get home for Christmas without causing a spike in coronavirus infections.

    They'll be given staggered departure dates in the week to 9 December, when all lectures and seminars will need to move online.

    Assistant Education Minister Jeremy Macon said dedicated hostels was one option being considered.

    Quote Message: The majority of young people have been very good and patient, and stuck with the guidelines, have followed the rules. University students again have had to stick with the rules in the UK, and so I am confident that, provided there is something provided for them, we should be able to manage the control of any infection from students coming back to Jersey." from Jeremy Macon Assistant Education Minister

  15. Posted at 9:19 11 Nov 20209:19 11 Nov 2020

    Chief minister 'relieved' at surviving no-confidence vote

    BBC Radio Jersey

    Jersey's chief minister says he's "absolutely relieved" after surviving a vote of no confidence in his leadership.

    Twenty-nine politicians voted to keep Senator John Le Fondre in post, while 19 voted for him to be replaced. Education Minister Tracey Vallois was the only States Member who refused to vote.

    It was laid following concerns raised about the government's chief executive taking a second job.

    Chief executive Charlie Parker announced his resignation on Monday as a result.

    Speaking to the BBC, Senator Le Fondre said he was very pleased with the result, and that the past 10 days had been the worst he had experienced in his political career.

    But he added that the vote was a "great message of support for everything that we've been doing".

    He is due to announce next week who will replace Senator Sam Mezec as children's and housing minister. Senator Mezec stood down from his post as part of his support for the no-confidence motion, which was also supported by his four Reform Jersey colleagues in the States.

    He has also to fill vacant assistant minister positions in the health, economic development and environment departments after Deputy Montfort Tadier and Senator Steve Pallett stood down from their roles.

    Mr Le Fondre said he had "some people in mind" whom he hoped would bring different experiences to the Council of Ministers.

    Quote Message: We listened to some of the comments and we're going to have to take those on board. But equally now we can focus on being back to business, back to dealing with Covid; and focusing on things like the hospital debate next week and the Government Plan in December... and move on." from Senator John Le Fondre Chief Minister

    We listened to some of the comments and we're going to have to take those on board. But equally now we can focus on being back to business, back to dealing with Covid; and focusing on things like the hospital debate next week and the Government Plan in December... and move on."

    Senator John Le FondreChief Minister

  16. Posted at 16:36 10 Nov 202016:36 10 Nov 2020

    Joey the poorly Jersey seal pup recovers at GSPCA

    Andrew Segal

    BBC News

    A grey seal pup rescued in Jersey has been brought over to Guernsey for treatment, animal charity the GSPCA has said.

    The young seal, named Joey and thought to be about 10 days old, was rescued by the British Divers Marine Life Rescue Jersey after reports of a poorly pup on Les Ecrehous.

    He was found to be a "very thin 18kgs" and was cared for overnight at New Era Vets before being taken over to Guernsey on the paper boat, the charity said.

    He is now in isolation at the GSPCA in an intensive care area for round-the-clock care.

    GSPCA Head of Marine Mammals Geoff George said Joey was "extremely thin" but "very feisty which is a good signâ despite being "extremely emaciated for his age".

    The GSPCA said without the rescue it was "very likely he wouldnât have survived in the wild".

    In the meantime, staff said the Channel Islands were "in the thick of seal pup season now" and anyone who saw seal pup should not approach it, "but do take a picture and send it in and give us a call so we know where they are and assess they are okay".

  17. Posted at 16:26 10 Nov 202016:26 10 Nov 2020

    More Covid cases confirmed at colleges

    Andrew Segal

    BBC South West

    More cases of coronavirus have been confirmed at colleges in Jersey, officials have said.

    The Department for Children, Young People, Education and Skills said six more cases had been confirmed at Jersey College for Girls since Thursday 5 November and three at Victoria College.

    Those affected were isolating at home.

    The colleges are remaining open following advice from environmental and public health staff, the department said.

    It added: "We are committed to supporting our students who have been impacted by the pandemic.

    "Students who have to be at home due to Public Health guidelines will continue to receive school work online, from today, so that they can continue with their education."

  18. Posted at 14:03 10 Nov 202014:03 10 Nov 2020

    Ex-civil service head 'not get extra quitting payout'

    BBC Radio Jersey

    The former head of Jersey's civil service will not be given an extra payout after stepping down from the role over his controversial second job, the chief minister has said.

    States' chief executive Charlie Parker said he had agreed to step aside following concerns over his taking a second job as a non-executive director of a UK investment trust company as his position had become a "distraction" from the government's agenda.

    Senator John Le Fondre said Mr Parker would get what was set out in his contract but would not be given residential qualifications.

    Politicians are debating a vote of no confidence in Mr Le Fondre as chief minister.

  20. Posted at 11:30 10 Nov 202011:30 10 Nov 2020

    Jersey sees 153 workers visiting without self-isolating

    BBC Radio Jersey

    Ministers have allowed 153 workers over two weeks to come to Jersey without having to self-isolate for coronavirus.

    Among them were aircraft engineers, healthcare and building workers and sewage works engineers.

    Ministers revealed the figures, covering 20 October to 4 November, to the panel that monitors Jersey's safer travel guidelines.

    Everyone coming to Jersey must isolate until they get a first negative test result, with most travellers face extra quarantine restrictions.

    But the government can allow workers to be exempt if they are critical to the running of a business.

    There are 115 known active cases of Covid-19 in Jersey.
